SIMPLE: supply
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Supply
<hw>Sup*ply"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Supplied</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Supplying</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[For
older <ets>supploy</ets>, F. <ets>suppl⟦eacute⟧er</ets>, OF. also
<ets>supployer</ets>, (assumed) LL. <ets>suppletare</ets>, from L.
<ets>supplere</ets>, <ets>suppletum</ets>; <ets>sub</ets> under +
<ets>plere</ets> to fill, akin to <ets>plenus</ets> full. See
<er>Plenty</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fill up, or keep full; to
furnish with what is wanted; to afford, or furnish with, a sufficiency;
<as>as, rivers are <ex>supplied</ex> by smaller streams; an aqueduct
<ex>supplies</ex> an artificial lake</as>; -- often followed by
<xex>with</xex> before the thing furnished; <as>as, to <ex>supply</ex> a
furnace with fuel; to <ex>supply</ex> soldiers with
ammunition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To serve instead of; to take the place of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Burning ships the banished sun <qex>supply</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sun was set, and Vesper, to <qex>supply</qex>⟦br⟧
His absent beams, had lighted up the sky.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To fill temporarily; to serve as substitute for
another in, as a vacant place or office; to occupy; to have possession
of; <as>as, to <ex>supply</ex> a pulpit</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give; to bring or furnish; to provide; <as>as, to
<ex>supply</ex> money for the war</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Prior.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To furnish; provide; administer; minister;
contribute; yield; accommodate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supply</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Supply
<hw>Sup*ply"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Supplies</plw>
<pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of supplying;
supplial.</def> <rj><au>A. Tucker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which supplies a want; sufficiency of things
for use or want.</def> Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <def>Auxiliary troops or reenforcements.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧My
promised <xex>supply</xex> of horsemen.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The food, and the like, which meets the daily
necessities of an army or other large body of men; store; -- used
chiefly in the plural; <as>as, the army was discontented for lack of
<ex>supplies</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <def>An amount of money provided, as by Parliament or
Congress, to meet the annual national expenditures; generally in the
plural; <as>as, to vote <ex>supplies</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(d)</sd> <def>A person who fills a place for a time; one who
supplies the place of another; a substitute; esp., a clergyman who
supplies a vacant pulpit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Stated supply</b></col> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld>, <cd>a
clergyman employed to supply a pulpit for a definite time, but not
settled as a pastor.</cd> <mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>Supply and
demand</b></col>. <fld>(Polit. Econ.)</fld> <cd>⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Demand</xex>
means the quantity of a given article which would be taken at a given
price. <xex>Supply</xex> means the quantity of that article which could
be had at that price.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>F. A. Walker.</au></cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supply</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Supply
<hw>Sup*ply"</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Serving to contain, deliver, or
regulate a supply of anything; <as>as, a <ex>supply</ex> tank or
valve</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Supply system</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
system of tubes and canals in sponges by means of which food and water
are absorbed. See <xex>Illust.</xex> of <er>Spongiae</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Supplyant</ent>⟦br⟧
